00:29:31.506 --> 00:29:32.950
ADRIAN MARTIN: I've had loads.

00:29:32.950 --> 00:29:36.310
Oh, my god, six years in that
kitchen, I've had so many.

00:29:36.310 --> 00:29:38.650
My worst one, I think, I
always look back on it.

00:29:38.650 --> 00:29:41.960
So we used to make these
sauces called veloutes.

00:29:41.960 --> 00:29:44.260
So Wednesday is
your main prep day.

00:29:44.260 --> 00:29:47.350
And your veloutes take in the
space of, like, five hours

00:29:47.350 --> 00:29:48.300
to make.

00:29:48.300 --> 00:29:50.560
Each veloute is finished
off with a liaison,

00:29:50.560 --> 00:29:53.450
which is literally egg yolk
and cream mixed together.

00:29:53.450 --> 00:29:57.770
And it gives the veloute a
shine and thickens it naturally.

00:29:57.770 --> 00:30:01.855
But what happened to me was
I made all the veloutes.

00:30:01.855 --> 00:30:03.730
They were always put in
these little buckets.

00:30:03.730 --> 00:30:04.720
There were labeled.

00:30:04.720 --> 00:30:06.850
They were placed into
this, like, chiller

00:30:06.850 --> 00:30:08.770
first to blast chill them.

00:30:08.770 --> 00:30:11.290
And then they were
placed into the cooler.

00:30:11.290 --> 00:30:14.500
But while I was pulling them
all out of the blast chiller,

00:30:14.500 --> 00:30:16.770
every single one of them
landed on the ground.

00:30:16.770 --> 00:30:19.380
So I was standing there
and I was like, oh, no.

00:30:19.380 --> 00:30:21.790
There is four
hours of work gone.

00:30:21.790 --> 00:30:24.560
So you can imagine-- and
then service is coming.

00:30:24.560 --> 00:30:27.810
And you have to try and
make these different types--

00:30:27.810 --> 00:30:31.750
prawn veloute, Thai
broth, mushroom veloute

00:30:31.750 --> 00:30:33.520
with grated truffle
in there that's worth,

00:30:33.520 --> 00:30:35.590
like, thousands of
euros and stuff.

00:30:35.590 --> 00:30:39.110
So you can imagine what it's--

00:30:39.110 --> 00:30:40.050
it was a 'mare.

00:30:40.050 --> 00:30:40.958
SPEAKER 1: OK.

