00:30:50.790 --> 00:30:53.580
AUDIENCE: You say we should
cook like our grandparents.

00:30:53.580 --> 00:30:56.340
So how do you feel about the
more modernist techniques

00:30:56.340 --> 00:30:57.794
that are out there these days?

00:30:57.794 --> 00:31:00.210
ADRIAN MARTIN: A lot of the
modern techniques-- obviously,

00:31:00.210 --> 00:31:03.810
we cook like our grandparents,
like we look at our ingredients

00:31:03.810 --> 00:31:05.610
the same way that
they look at it.

00:31:05.610 --> 00:31:07.910
But obviously, the modern
techniques that come in

00:31:07.910 --> 00:31:11.340
fit in so nicely
with it, as well.

00:31:11.340 --> 00:31:14.850
I believe that if you look back,
it's just really looking back

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:18.110
to basics the way they used
to shop rather than cook.

00:31:18.110 --> 00:31:20.100
But the modern
techniques of cooking,

00:31:20.100 --> 00:31:22.729
using different types of
spices and seasons and stuff,

00:31:22.729 --> 00:31:23.770
are absolutely brilliant.

00:31:23.770 --> 00:31:26.545
Yeah.

00:31:26.545 --> 00:31:29.323
SPEAKER 1: And back over here.

00:31:29.323 --> 00:31:30.557
ADRIAN MARTIN: Cool.

