00:32:39.770 --> 00:32:40.870
It really helped me.

00:32:40.870 --> 00:32:43.740
I also went over, then,
to work in Ramsay's place.

00:32:43.740 --> 00:32:45.030
Best meal I've ever had.

00:32:45.030 --> 00:32:46.610
I was there for,
like, three weeks.

00:32:46.610 --> 00:32:48.304
So you can do stages in there.

00:32:48.304 --> 00:32:49.470
It's in Royal Hospital Road.

00:32:49.470 --> 00:32:51.330
He has three Michelin stars.

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:53.970
And you know I was
saying, I'm a believer

00:32:53.970 --> 00:32:56.070
that the wheel that squeaks
the most gets the oil.

00:32:56.070 --> 00:32:57.780
I was literally the
most annoying person

00:32:57.780 --> 00:32:59.571
ever for those three
weeks in that kitchen.

00:32:59.571 --> 00:33:01.756
I'd say they really liked
to see the end of me.

00:33:01.756 --> 00:33:05.230
But travel around as much as
you can and get your degree.

00:33:05.230 --> 00:33:07.090
But there's loads of
opportunities out there

00:33:07.090 --> 00:33:09.540
in cooking itself, not just
being a chef in a kitchen

00:33:09.540 --> 00:33:10.950
or running a kitchen.

00:33:10.950 --> 00:33:11.810
I'm 25.

00:33:11.810 --> 00:33:13.072
Everyone keeps asking
me, why don't you

00:33:13.072 --> 00:33:13.900
have your own restaurant yet?

00:33:13.900 --> 00:33:15.358
Why don't you have
your restaurant?

00:33:15.358 --> 00:33:17.670
There's no point in me having
a restaurant when I'm 25.

00:33:17.670 --> 00:33:20.770
I'd be better off having
a restaurant when I'm 35.

00:33:20.770 --> 00:33:23.160
So then I have a lot more
experience behind me.

00:33:23.160 --> 00:33:25.284
I know exactly what I
want to do at that stage.

00:33:25.284 --> 00:33:26.700
Because I'm only
figuring out what

00:33:26.700 --> 00:33:28.641
I want to do as I go along now.

00:33:30.874 --> 00:33:33.040
AUDIENCE: My question was,
do you have a restaurant?

00:33:33.040 --> 00:33:34.062
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:34.062 --> 00:33:35.020
ADRIAN MARTIN: I don't.

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:35.440
No, no.

00:33:35.440 --> 00:33:36.840
AUDIENCE: And the
second question

00:33:36.840 --> 00:33:39.360
is, as you don't have a
restaurant, two or three names

00:33:39.360 --> 00:33:41.950
that you suggest to eat in
Dublin that you say, wow.

00:33:41.950 --> 00:33:44.230
ADRIAN MARTIN: Oh, OK.

00:33:44.230 --> 00:33:48.687
Obviously, The Greenhouse
is absolutely amazing.

00:33:48.687 --> 00:33:50.520
Have any of you ever
been to the Greenhouse?

00:33:50.520 --> 00:33:51.146
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:33:51.146 --> 00:33:52.145
ADRIAN MARTIN: You have?

00:33:52.145 --> 00:33:52.972
What do you think?

00:33:52.972 --> 00:33:54.300
AUDIENCE: Best
restaurant up town.

00:33:54.300 --> 00:33:55.133
ADRIAN MARTIN: Yeah.

00:33:55.133 --> 00:33:56.180
It's insanely good.

00:33:56.180 --> 00:33:57.625
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:33:57.625 --> 00:34:00.000
ADRIAN MARTIN: Did you have
the little beetroot meringues

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:01.466
with the pistachio?

00:34:01.466 --> 00:34:02.132
AUDIENCE: I did.

00:34:02.132 --> 00:34:02.610
Actually, I did.

00:34:02.610 --> 00:34:04.109
ADRIAN MARTIN: I
robbed that recipe.

00:34:04.109 --> 00:34:06.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:06.580 --> 00:34:08.340
That's a great little thing.

00:34:08.340 --> 00:34:11.400
That restaurant is insane.

00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:14.289
I suppose I would go
outside of Dublin.

00:34:14.289 --> 00:34:15.330
I was in the Cliff House.

00:34:15.330 --> 00:34:16.830
I actually didn't
think it was going

00:34:16.830 --> 00:34:21.060
to be that nice-- the
Cliff House in Waterford.

00:34:21.060 --> 00:34:23.352
The best hotel I've
ever stayed in.

00:34:23.352 --> 00:34:25.560
If you leave your room,
there's a sensor on the door.

00:34:25.560 --> 00:34:27.726
As soon as you leave your
room, these little fairies

00:34:27.726 --> 00:34:29.850
come in and make your
bed and everything.

00:34:29.850 --> 00:34:32.569
And it has a Michelin-star
restaurant on-site, as well.

00:34:32.569 --> 00:34:33.610
It's really, really good.

00:34:33.610 --> 00:34:34.600
It's worth traveling there.

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:34.760
SPEAKER 1: OK.

00:34:34.760 --> 00:34:35.320
Great.

00:34:35.320 --> 00:34:35.679
Thank you.

00:34:35.679 --> 00:34:36.064
Yeah.

00:34:36.064 --> 00:34:37.105
The Cliff House is great.

00:34:37.105 --> 00:34:39.179
And they have one in
town, as well, don't they?

00:34:39.179 --> 00:34:39.730
Are they linked?

00:34:39.730 --> 00:34:40.938
ADRIAN MARTIN: The sister's--

00:34:40.938 --> 00:34:42.360
SPEAKER 1: Yeah, the sister.

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:45.000
So while the audience is
thinking of another question,

00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:48.060
I read that when
you have time, you

00:34:48.060 --> 00:34:52.370
try to get out and do a little
bit of running now and again.

00:34:52.370 --> 00:34:55.770
We have any runners
in the audience today?

00:34:55.770 --> 00:34:56.742
Yeah, got a few.

00:34:56.742 --> 00:34:57.920
ADRIAN MARTIN: Well, they
probably put me all to shame.

00:34:57.920 --> 00:34:58.919
SPEAKER 1: That's great.

00:34:58.919 --> 00:35:00.840
What's your post-run treat?

00:35:03.360 --> 00:35:04.530
ADRIAN MARTIN: I don't know.

00:35:04.530 --> 00:35:05.640
I used to have bananas.

00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:07.500
I used to play
football as a kid.

00:35:07.500 --> 00:35:09.285
I used to eat a banana.

00:35:09.285 --> 00:35:12.250
I had two bananas before
a football match years ago

00:35:12.250 --> 00:35:13.320
and everything came up.

00:35:13.320 --> 00:35:15.460
So I don't like bananas anymore.

00:35:15.460 --> 00:35:16.950
I'd recommend a banana.

00:35:16.950 --> 00:35:19.180
Just one, not two.

00:35:19.180 --> 00:35:19.930
But I don't know--

00:35:19.930 --> 00:35:20.260
SPEAKER 1: Is that all?

00:35:20.260 --> 00:35:21.759
ADRIAN MARTIN:
--what I normally do.

00:35:21.759 --> 00:35:23.750
I normally get this
idea in my head.

00:35:23.750 --> 00:35:26.490
I'm kind of a very
fidgety person, always

00:35:26.490 --> 00:35:28.710
wanting to move about
and go on the go.

00:35:28.710 --> 00:35:31.060
So if I get it in my head
that I'm going for a run,

00:35:31.060 --> 00:35:34.710
I'm literally in the
run before I actually

00:35:34.710 --> 00:35:36.900
think of what I'm going
to eat beforehand.

00:35:36.900 --> 00:35:38.717
And I'm always
just a big believer

00:35:38.717 --> 00:35:40.550
in eating your breakfast,
lunch, and dinner.

00:35:40.550 --> 00:35:43.010
Eating your three meals,
cooking them yourself,

00:35:43.010 --> 00:35:45.220
and eating nicely.

00:35:45.220 --> 00:35:48.260
SPEAKER 1: I run so that I
can add in an extra meal.

00:35:48.260 --> 00:35:49.490
ADRIAN MARTIN: I like that.

00:35:49.490 --> 00:35:52.160
SPEAKER 1: I know what I'm going
to eat before I go for my run.

00:35:52.160 --> 00:35:55.740
We have another few
questions over here.

00:35:55.740 --> 00:35:56.600
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:35:56.600 --> 00:35:58.726
I actually wanted to ask
a bit more about shopping,

00:35:58.726 --> 00:36:00.725
because you mentioned
it's very important to buy

00:36:00.725 --> 00:36:01.940
good ingredients and things.

00:36:01.940 --> 00:36:03.875
And I think it's
often stopped us

00:36:03.875 --> 00:36:05.250
from cooking when
you don't have,

00:36:05.250 --> 00:36:06.650
at home, some ingredients.

00:36:06.650 --> 00:36:09.170
So what is the best advice, how
to organize your shopping so

00:36:09.170 --> 00:36:11.240
that you're not really
going with a book

00:36:11.240 --> 00:36:14.340
and choosing three items,
but more holistically,

00:36:14.340 --> 00:36:16.370
so it kind of gives you
inspiration for cooking?

00:36:16.370 --> 00:36:17.370
ADRIAN MARTIN: Yeah.

00:36:17.370 --> 00:36:19.260
I put a little section
in the book there.

00:36:19.260 --> 00:36:21.880
It's "What to Have
in Your Cupboard."

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:26.100
So there's a selection of
spices and oils and stuff.

00:36:26.100 --> 00:36:29.250
If you have-- you can probably
look in your cupboard already.

00:36:29.250 --> 00:36:31.415
And you look at that
little list and it'll say--

00:36:31.415 --> 00:36:33.290
you can probably look
in it and then be like,

00:36:33.290 --> 00:36:35.750
oh, I actually have the
majority of that stuff already.

00:36:35.750 --> 00:36:39.290
The book is literally
anything that

00:36:39.290 --> 00:36:44.270
is easily accessible, bought,
in all your shops in Ireland.

00:36:44.270 --> 00:36:47.780
And for me, when I'm
cooking, I probably

00:36:47.780 --> 00:36:50.910
do it the wrong way, which is
a lot more expensive to do.

00:36:50.910 --> 00:36:53.370
I buy ingredients every day.

00:36:53.370 --> 00:36:54.770
So I go shopping every day.

00:36:54.770 --> 00:36:59.540
So if I'm cooking my
meals, the day before,

00:36:59.540 --> 00:37:01.955
I'll do my shopping
for just that day.

00:37:01.955 --> 00:37:04.790
I'd recommend maybe going on a
Sunday and gathering together.

00:37:04.790 --> 00:37:07.520
So you know exactly what
you're making all week

00:37:07.520 --> 00:37:10.610
so that you stick to a
plan, more than anything.

00:37:10.610 --> 00:37:11.600
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:11.600 --> 00:37:13.016
ADRIAN MARTIN:
Yeah, a little bit.

00:37:13.016 --> 00:37:13.880
But I love it.

00:37:13.880 --> 00:37:18.070
My thing is if I'm too lazy
this evening to go shopping,

00:37:18.070 --> 00:37:19.820
I'll have something
in the cupboard there.

00:37:19.820 --> 00:37:23.210
I'll look at the ingredients
and go, right, I can make--

00:37:23.210 --> 00:37:24.060
I don't know.

00:37:24.060 --> 00:37:27.009
I've got prawns there,
I've got noodles--

00:37:27.009 --> 00:37:27.800
like, rice noodles.

00:37:27.800 --> 00:37:29.392
Let's make Pad Thai, you know?

00:37:29.392 --> 00:37:31.100
Because you'll have
little bits and bobs.

00:37:31.100 --> 00:37:34.550
You can always add in different
types of ingredients and stuff.

00:37:34.550 --> 00:37:36.920
And that's kind of
the way I look at it.

00:37:36.920 --> 00:37:40.860
You can even get creative with
food, have some fun with it,

00:37:40.860 --> 00:37:41.660
as well.

00:37:41.660 --> 00:37:43.260
If you're too lazy
one of the evenings

00:37:43.260 --> 00:37:45.740
to actually do
something, have a look

00:37:45.740 --> 00:37:47.450
at what you have
instead of picking up

00:37:47.450 --> 00:37:51.590
the phone a dialing Just
Eat, whatever it is.

00:37:51.590 --> 00:37:54.140
Have a look at what you have
and I can put money on it,

00:37:54.140 --> 00:37:59.094
you can put together something
really fast, really easy.

00:37:59.094 --> 00:38:00.260
A lot quicker than takeaway.

00:38:06.410 --> 00:38:08.150
AUDIENCE: Thank you
so much for the talk.

00:38:08.150 --> 00:38:10.483
Before I worked here, I worked
also in a five-star hotel

00:38:10.483 --> 00:38:11.550
and had chefs every day.

00:38:11.550 --> 00:38:13.216
And I think you are
the most humble chef

00:38:13.216 --> 00:38:16.460
I've ever met, which I think
is really, really cool.

00:38:16.460 --> 00:38:18.417
And I have a light question.

00:38:18.417 --> 00:38:20.750
What is one thing that you
really dislike, but sometimes

00:38:20.750 --> 00:38:22.416
you have to prepare
it for someone else,

00:38:22.416 --> 00:38:25.234
but you really hate it?

00:38:25.234 --> 00:38:26.400
ADRIAN MARTIN: I don't know.

00:38:26.400 --> 00:38:27.619
I don't mind-- what?

00:38:27.619 --> 00:38:28.660
AUDIENCE: You hate sushi.

00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:29.860
ADRIAN MARTIN: Oh, yeah, sushi.

00:38:29.860 --> 00:38:30.410
Yeah.

00:38:30.410 --> 00:38:32.535
I've made sushi so many
times, I just can't eat it.

00:38:32.535 --> 00:38:33.300
Agh.

00:38:33.300 --> 00:38:34.490
No.

00:38:34.490 --> 00:38:36.050
No, it's not for me at all.

00:38:36.050 --> 00:38:36.620
Sorry.

00:38:36.620 --> 00:38:38.580
There are just some
things that aren't for me.

00:38:38.580 --> 00:38:41.030
But yeah.

00:38:41.030 --> 00:38:41.940
I just think it's--

00:38:41.940 --> 00:38:43.460
I don't know what it is.

00:38:43.460 --> 00:38:45.860
Just can't get my
head around it.

00:38:45.860 --> 00:38:48.090
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:48.590 --> 00:38:50.100
What else do I not like?

00:38:50.100 --> 00:38:52.537
Banoffee pie because
bananas, you know?

00:38:52.537 --> 00:38:53.910
[LAUGHTER]

00:38:53.910 --> 00:38:55.270
Anything to do with bananas.

00:38:55.270 --> 00:38:58.120
Oh, also, what gets
on my nerves, right,

00:38:58.120 --> 00:39:00.600
is do you know when you
have a smoothie and it says,

00:39:00.600 --> 00:39:01.410
mango smoothie?

00:39:01.410 --> 00:39:02.075
OK?

00:39:02.075 --> 00:39:03.800
But they put banana in it?

00:39:03.800 --> 00:39:05.200
It's a banana smoothie, come on.

00:39:05.200 --> 00:39:06.702
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:06.702 --> 00:39:07.910
It just tastes like a banana.

00:39:10.674 --> 00:39:11.840
AUDIENCE: How are you doing?

00:39:11.840 --> 00:39:13.400
ADRIAN MARTIN: Hi.

00:39:13.400 --> 00:39:15.360
AUDIENCE: I was giving
a look to your book,

00:39:15.360 --> 00:39:19.150
and there is different
kind of food in it.

00:39:19.150 --> 00:39:22.340
There's a bit o Italian,
there is a bit of Indian.

00:39:22.340 --> 00:39:23.700
So I have two questions.

00:39:23.700 --> 00:39:26.150
The first one is, where
do you get inspiration

00:39:26.150 --> 00:39:29.000
when you of a new recipe?

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:30.890
And the second question
is, I have a dinner

00:39:30.890 --> 00:39:32.570
party coming next week--

00:39:32.570 --> 00:39:34.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:34.290 --> 00:39:35.690
I swear to God.

00:39:35.690 --> 00:39:39.230
And I would like to have a
suggestion from your book

00:39:39.230 --> 00:39:40.680
for a starter and a main.

00:39:40.680 --> 00:39:41.596
ADRIAN MARTIN: OK, OK.

00:39:41.596 --> 00:39:43.220
I like that, actually.

00:39:43.220 --> 00:39:46.020
So what was the first question?

00:39:46.020 --> 00:39:47.440
I've forgotten it.

00:39:47.440 --> 00:39:49.190
AUDIENCE: Your
inspiration, where you take

00:39:49.190 --> 00:39:49.950
inspiration in the recipes.

00:39:49.950 --> 00:39:51.575
ADRIAN MARTIN: The
inspiration behind--

00:39:51.575 --> 00:39:54.980
so you see it's all
broken down into chapters?

00:39:54.980 --> 00:39:56.492
I've traveled to
all these places

00:39:56.492 --> 00:39:58.200
to try all these
different types of food.

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:02.890
You can see, in Japan
there, when I was in Japan,

00:40:02.890 --> 00:40:05.540
I got this lovely little
scallop on the street.

00:40:05.540 --> 00:40:06.360
I was amazed by it.

00:40:06.360 --> 00:40:09.287
It was just this guy who was
standing at this little stall.

00:40:09.287 --> 00:40:10.620
He had the shell on the scallop.

00:40:10.620 --> 00:40:13.700
He took the coral off and he
had a blowtorch and he just--

00:40:13.700 --> 00:40:16.260
sea salt-- blowtorched
the scallop there.

00:40:16.260 --> 00:40:18.237
And it was in a--

00:40:18.237 --> 00:40:20.570
served, give you a little
fork, and you eat your scallop

00:40:20.570 --> 00:40:22.235
on the go, blowtorched scallop.

00:40:22.235 --> 00:40:23.510
And I was obsessed with that.

00:40:23.510 --> 00:40:25.910
So kind of the inspiration
behind-- you'll

00:40:25.910 --> 00:40:28.550
see each recipe has a story.

00:40:28.550 --> 00:40:30.660
On top, each recipe has
a little story there.

00:40:30.660 --> 00:40:33.920
And there's a pancake in
there called a socca pancake.

00:40:33.920 --> 00:40:37.320
So in Nice, there's
Nicoise cuisine.

00:40:37.320 --> 00:40:39.230
They have their own
type of cuisine that's

00:40:39.230 --> 00:40:41.850
completely different to France.

00:40:41.850 --> 00:40:46.120
And they have all their own
different ethnic dishes.

00:40:46.120 --> 00:40:48.290
The socca, I was
obsessed with it.

00:40:48.290 --> 00:40:50.690
Because in the market
square in Nice,

00:40:50.690 --> 00:40:53.012
when you walk into
the market square,

00:40:53.012 --> 00:40:54.095
there's this massive line.

00:40:54.095 --> 00:40:55.636
And I was like,
what's going on here?

00:40:55.636 --> 00:40:58.080
There's this big line lining
up for this type of pancake.

00:40:58.080 --> 00:40:59.420
And I walked up.

00:40:59.420 --> 00:41:02.030
Anyway, they make it
there at the stall.

00:41:02.030 --> 00:41:05.330
It's a little like, I
suppose, bike and cart.

00:41:05.330 --> 00:41:08.000
And when they make it, they
mix it up and roll it out.

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:09.834
They place it onto this
little type of cart.

00:41:09.834 --> 00:41:12.374
It goes through a pizza oven,
it comes back in seven minutes.

00:41:12.374 --> 00:41:13.920
Next thing, this
massive line forms,

00:41:13.920 --> 00:41:16.430
and it's this crispy
chickpea pancake.

00:41:16.430 --> 00:41:18.710
But every recipe inside
there has a story

00:41:18.710 --> 00:41:20.720
of where I've seen
it before and I

00:41:20.720 --> 00:41:22.582
wanted to learn how to make it.

00:41:22.582 --> 00:41:24.290
And then, what I was
saying was the wheel

00:41:24.290 --> 00:41:25.670
that squeaks gets the oil.

00:41:25.670 --> 00:41:27.450
When I was in Nice, I was
like, show me how to make that.

00:41:27.450 --> 00:41:28.610
I'm not leaving until
you show me how.

00:41:28.610 --> 00:41:29.110
You know?

00:41:29.110 --> 00:41:32.230
And that's kind of where I
learned my recipes and stuff,

00:41:32.230 --> 00:41:34.750
from traveling and all.

00:41:34.750 --> 00:41:36.477
For your dinner party--

00:41:36.477 --> 00:41:38.350
AUDIENCE: Pick two, please.

00:41:38.350 --> 00:41:40.100
ADRIAN MARTIN: Scallops
and black pudding.

00:41:40.100 --> 00:41:41.516
Very, very simple
to put together.

00:41:41.516 --> 00:41:48.384
It literally takes you, like,
30 seconds to two minutes--

00:41:48.384 --> 00:41:50.470
like, two minutes, each
side of your scallop

00:41:50.470 --> 00:41:51.630
will cook your scallops.

00:41:51.630 --> 00:41:53.120
Black pudding on the same pan.

00:41:53.120 --> 00:41:54.536
How many people
have you got over?

00:41:54.536 --> 00:41:55.740
Six, is it?

00:41:55.740 --> 00:41:56.380
AUDIENCE: Four.

00:41:56.380 --> 00:41:57.213
ADRIAN MARTIN: Four.

00:41:57.213 --> 00:42:00.330
So literally four scallops each,
four pieces of black pudding.

00:42:00.330 --> 00:42:04.184
A Granny Smith apple, which is
sliced up really, really thin,

00:42:04.184 --> 00:42:05.600
mixed through your
lamb's lettuce.

00:42:05.600 --> 00:42:08.022
Lemon juice, olive
oil, sea salt.

00:42:08.022 --> 00:42:10.520
Put that in the middle of the
plate, arrange your scallops.

00:42:10.520 --> 00:42:12.603
Make sure you get a lovely
color on your scallops.

00:42:12.603 --> 00:42:15.627
AUDIENCE: I asked you for an
easy recipe, a very easy one.

00:42:15.627 --> 00:42:17.210
ADRIAN MARTIN: What
else could you do?

00:42:17.210 --> 00:42:19.185
So you're-- oh, a lovely
starter-- actually,

00:42:19.185 --> 00:42:21.560
it's not in the book, but a
lovely starter you could do--

00:42:21.560 --> 00:42:22.934
because we've got
nectarines that

00:42:22.934 --> 00:42:25.940
are in season at the
moment, if you get yourself

00:42:25.940 --> 00:42:28.190
a little bit of
ricotta cheese, you

00:42:28.190 --> 00:42:30.530
get yourself some
sriracha sauce.

00:42:30.530 --> 00:42:32.810
Drizzle in some sriracha
sauce into your ricotta.

00:42:32.810 --> 00:42:35.480
Lemon juice, pinch of
salt. Mix that together.

00:42:35.480 --> 00:42:37.670
Get yourself some
toasted sourdough bread.

00:42:37.670 --> 00:42:39.440
Spread that on your
sourdough bread

00:42:39.440 --> 00:42:41.750
and get yourself
a dry griddle pan.

00:42:41.750 --> 00:42:45.380
And griddle little
segments of your nectarine

00:42:45.380 --> 00:42:49.572
or peach and place those
on top with some rocket.

00:42:49.572 --> 00:42:51.280
AUDIENCE: Now you're
talking like a chef.

00:42:51.280 --> 00:42:52.113
ADRIAN MARTIN: Yeah.

00:42:52.113 --> 00:42:52.940
AUDIENCE: You know?

00:42:52.940 --> 00:42:54.547
And a little, I
don't know, dessert?

00:42:54.547 --> 00:42:55.505
ADRIAN MARTIN: Dessert.

00:42:55.505 --> 00:42:56.765
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:56.765 --> 00:43:01.150
There's After Eight
cheesecake there.

00:43:01.150 --> 00:43:04.740
So I had a big obsession
for desserts in there.

00:43:04.740 --> 00:43:06.740
There's After Eight
cheesecake, which is insane.

00:43:06.740 --> 00:43:09.560
And also, your main course.

00:43:09.560 --> 00:43:12.705
If you're looking at the sides,
have the little try at Easter--

00:43:12.705 --> 00:43:13.830
AUDIENCE: It looks amazing.

00:43:13.830 --> 00:43:15.880
ADRIAN MARTIN: It
looks good, doesn't it?

00:43:15.880 --> 00:43:18.220
There's Hasselback potatoes.

00:43:18.220 --> 00:43:20.704
So if you have a little
look at your side dishes,

00:43:20.704 --> 00:43:22.120
these Hasselback
potatoes, they're

00:43:22.120 --> 00:43:24.660
literally, like, the
most insanely crispy,

00:43:24.660 --> 00:43:26.950
fluffy potatoes you'll ever
have in your life ever.

00:43:26.950 --> 00:43:28.480
They're really, really good.

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:29.313
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:43:29.313 --> 00:43:31.618
ADRIAN MARTIN: Thank you.

00:43:31.618 --> 00:43:32.980
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:43:32.980 --> 00:43:36.940
I'm just wondering,
so when I was 15, 16,

00:43:36.940 --> 00:43:39.910
I had the urge to
become a chef, as well.

00:43:39.910 --> 00:43:42.760
However, my parents--
especially my dad-- was like,

00:43:42.760 --> 00:43:45.610
no, you need to go to uni,
and you've got your brains.

00:43:45.610 --> 00:43:48.070
And in the Netherlands,
because I'm Dutch,

00:43:48.070 --> 00:43:49.670
you have to have
a certain degree

00:43:49.670 --> 00:43:52.330
to go into cooking school.

00:43:52.330 --> 00:43:53.950
And I was--

00:43:53.950 --> 00:43:55.570
I wasn't eligible to go in.

00:43:55.570 --> 00:43:58.390
But I'm still doubting
until the day of today

00:43:58.390 --> 00:44:01.220
whether I should do
a cooking school.

00:44:01.220 --> 00:44:03.730
However, my question to you
is, obviously, you started

00:44:03.730 --> 00:44:05.500
when you was really young.

00:44:05.500 --> 00:44:07.870
Have you ever felt
like you missed out

00:44:07.870 --> 00:44:10.450
on your youth whilst
other friends were doing,

00:44:10.450 --> 00:44:14.590
I don't know, going out,
meeting other girls or guys,

00:44:14.590 --> 00:44:15.610
going out for drinks?

00:44:15.610 --> 00:44:17.557
And I know you're
really passionate,

00:44:17.557 --> 00:44:20.140
but I'm just wondering, have you
ever felt like you missed out

00:44:20.140 --> 00:44:22.970
or that you wanted to
change to something else?

00:44:22.970 --> 00:44:24.820
And what would be
your advice to people

00:44:24.820 --> 00:44:27.970
that have had a dream
similar to you, as well,

00:44:27.970 --> 00:44:32.335
but couldn't because of, I
don't know, college or whatever?

00:44:32.335 --> 00:44:34.340
ADRIAN MARTIN: My thing was--

00:44:34.340 --> 00:44:36.760
I suppose I went through
so many different phases

00:44:36.760 --> 00:44:39.010
since I was working there.

00:44:39.010 --> 00:44:40.960
You go through so many
different emotions

00:44:40.960 --> 00:44:42.510
because you're seeing
the same people

00:44:42.510 --> 00:44:47.400
every single day of the
week, your 80 hours a week.

00:44:47.400 --> 00:44:50.470
So literally, your
emotions change like that.

00:44:50.470 --> 00:44:51.700
And yeah.

00:44:51.700 --> 00:44:55.810
I went through so many
different kind of emotions.

00:44:55.810 --> 00:44:56.940
All my friends--

00:44:56.940 --> 00:44:59.620
I have two friends, believe
it or not, now because of it.

00:44:59.620 --> 00:45:02.406
Two of my best friends have
stuck with me from school

00:45:02.406 --> 00:45:08.000
and literally have been
the best guys to me

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:11.270
and understood that I had
those long hours and stuff.

00:45:11.270 --> 00:45:15.070
But the amount of friends that
just literally dropped and left

00:45:15.070 --> 00:45:17.050
because, you know,
they were asking you,

00:45:17.050 --> 00:45:18.180
oh, we're going here.

00:45:18.180 --> 00:45:19.390
Let's go here.

00:45:19.390 --> 00:45:20.620
You miss out on everything.

00:45:20.620 --> 00:45:22.161
You really do miss
out on everything,

00:45:22.161 --> 00:45:24.690
but it was a sacrifice
I had to take.

00:45:24.690 --> 00:45:27.010
Looking back,
probably my parents

00:45:27.010 --> 00:45:28.260
were the biggest help to me.

00:45:28.260 --> 00:45:30.310
They were always
like, oh, just wait

00:45:30.310 --> 00:45:31.570
until you get to your future.

00:45:31.570 --> 00:45:32.945
You never know
what you could do.

00:45:32.945 --> 00:45:35.920
You could be maybe working in a
college as a college lecturer.

00:45:35.920 --> 00:45:37.059
You could be maybe--

00:45:37.059 --> 00:45:37.600
I don't know.

00:45:37.600 --> 00:45:41.020
My dad was always a believer
that if you believe something,

00:45:41.020 --> 00:45:45.130
follow through in it, and
it'll work out in the end.

00:45:45.130 --> 00:45:47.810
It was a lot of hard
work, long hours.

00:45:47.810 --> 00:45:49.260
There's even Bon Appetit.

00:45:49.260 --> 00:45:51.470
I will give you an example.

00:45:51.470 --> 00:45:55.770
Oliver Dunne was the chef who
trained under Gordon Ramsay.

00:45:55.770 --> 00:45:59.350
For six-- I think it was six,
seven months I was there,

00:45:59.350 --> 00:46:01.940
every day, I stood
here on pastry.

00:46:01.940 --> 00:46:04.720
Oliver stood here, who was
the owner of the restaurant,

00:46:04.720 --> 00:46:06.610
and shouting at me,
and gave me abuse,

00:46:06.610 --> 00:46:11.470
and told me I'm a f'ing
idiot, and you're a--

00:46:11.470 --> 00:46:13.140
whatever-- all day.

00:46:13.140 --> 00:46:16.870
So you'd listen to that
all day from someone.

00:46:16.870 --> 00:46:18.230
Yeah, it's tough.

00:46:18.230 --> 00:46:20.147
It really is a tough career.

00:46:20.147 --> 00:46:21.230
It's getting a lot better.

00:46:21.230 --> 00:46:24.730
There's a lot more help
out there for chefs.

00:46:24.730 --> 00:46:28.360
There's a massive shortage
in them in Ireland.

00:46:28.360 --> 00:46:32.350
There's a shortage
of about 5,000 chefs.

00:46:32.350 --> 00:46:35.740
And the reason for that,
they blame the qualification

00:46:35.740 --> 00:46:36.680
schemes, but it's not.

00:46:36.680 --> 00:46:39.210
It's the treatment
that chefs are

00:46:39.210 --> 00:46:40.750
receiving in the restaurants.

00:46:40.750 --> 00:46:43.420
It's not the way to
treat people at all.

00:46:43.420 --> 00:46:46.630
There is a lot more rules and
regulations coming in for us.

00:46:46.630 --> 00:46:49.260
Some of the places
are disgraceful.

00:46:49.260 --> 00:46:52.150
Let's be honest, having
pots and pans thrown at you

00:46:52.150 --> 00:46:53.890
is not very nice.

00:46:53.890 --> 00:46:58.890
But obviously, those guys
are being sought after.

00:46:58.890 --> 00:47:01.910
But I recommend, if you
want to do something

00:47:01.910 --> 00:47:06.460
and you believe that the end
goal is you get an amazing job,

00:47:06.460 --> 00:47:09.595
an amazing life, I think
follow through with it.

00:47:09.595 --> 00:47:10.325
Yeah.

00:47:10.325 --> 00:47:11.200
SPEAKER 1: Very good.

00:47:11.200 --> 00:47:13.930
Certainly sounds like there
is room in the market for you

00:47:13.930 --> 00:47:14.830
if you feel like--

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:15.020
ADRIAN MARTIN:
There's lots of room.

00:47:15.020 --> 00:47:15.914
Loads of room.

00:47:15.914 --> 00:47:16.860
Loads of room.

00:47:16.860 --> 00:47:17.485
SPEAKER 1: There's
one more question

00:47:17.485 --> 00:47:18.734
over on this side of the room.

00:47:21.770 --> 00:47:22.330
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:47:22.330 --> 00:47:25.570
When you were talking right
now about your experience,

00:47:25.570 --> 00:47:27.970
it reminded me
about a movie, and I

00:47:27.970 --> 00:47:30.400
wanted to ask you which
are-- like, for example,

00:47:30.400 --> 00:47:33.190
for me, the cooking movie
I love is "Ratatouille."

00:47:33.190 --> 00:47:34.690
It's my cooking movie.

00:47:34.690 --> 00:47:38.982
Which are your favorite
cooking-related movies?

00:47:38.982 --> 00:47:39.940
ADRIAN MARTIN: I love--

00:47:42.870 --> 00:47:44.860
what have I watched recently?

00:47:44.860 --> 00:47:46.220
I'm obsessed with cooking shows.

00:47:46.220 --> 00:47:49.040
I watch so many of them.

00:47:49.040 --> 00:47:51.084
Have you ever seen
"Man versus Food?"

00:47:51.084 --> 00:47:52.042
AUDIENCE: Adam Richman.

00:47:52.042 --> 00:47:52.920
ADRIAN MARTIN: Huh?

00:47:52.920 --> 00:47:53.640
AUDIENCE: Adam Richman.

00:47:53.640 --> 00:47:54.130
ADRIAN MARTIN: Adam Richman.

00:47:54.130 --> 00:47:54.629
Yeah.

00:47:54.629 --> 00:47:57.460
I actually met Adam recently.

00:47:57.460 --> 00:47:59.890
He came to Guinness.

00:47:59.890 --> 00:48:01.400
I was obsessed with that show.

00:48:01.400 --> 00:48:02.890
So when we met Adam, we
were literally like--

00:48:02.890 --> 00:48:03.240
[GASPS]

00:48:03.240 --> 00:48:04.531
I was literally standing there.

00:48:04.531 --> 00:48:06.662
I was like, I
can't speak to him.

00:48:06.662 --> 00:48:09.310
But my friend
thought it'd be funny

00:48:09.310 --> 00:48:10.675
that we were, like, messing.

00:48:10.675 --> 00:48:13.050
We were just like, oh, let's
get him to do the challenge.

00:48:13.050 --> 00:48:15.250
But no, he wasn't up for it.

00:48:15.250 --> 00:48:18.610
I love so many different
types of cooking shows.

00:48:18.610 --> 00:48:20.170
My all-time favorite
cooking show

00:48:20.170 --> 00:48:24.700
ever is "The F Word"
by Gordon Ramsay.

00:48:24.700 --> 00:48:27.130
Probably the best put
together cooking show ever.

00:48:27.130 --> 00:48:29.470
It's so good to watch.

00:48:29.470 --> 00:48:32.670
Gordon's such a fast-paced chef.

00:48:32.670 --> 00:48:34.630
He's fiery, obviously.

00:48:34.630 --> 00:48:38.740
But it's so interesting
to see ordinary people

00:48:38.740 --> 00:48:40.390
come in and work
inside his kitchen

00:48:40.390 --> 00:48:43.630
and serve food out to an
amazing set of guests and stuff.

00:48:43.630 --> 00:48:45.040
It's a really, really good show.

00:48:45.040 --> 00:48:49.600
He's also set a new series
out in the US at the moment.

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:50.720
"The F Word" again, yeah.

00:48:50.720 --> 00:48:51.460
It's really good.

00:48:51.460 --> 00:48:51.720
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:51.720 --> 00:48:52.040
SPEAKER 1: OK.

00:48:52.040 --> 00:48:52.250
Great.

00:48:52.250 --> 00:48:52.750
Thank you.

00:48:52.750 --> 00:48:55.760
So I'll just ask one last
question before we close.

00:48:55.760 --> 00:48:57.520
I love that you've
created a book that's

00:48:57.520 --> 00:49:00.330
for the people on the
other end of the spectrum

00:49:00.330 --> 00:49:01.930
because, like you
were saying, it's

00:49:01.930 --> 00:49:04.460
so easy to drop
out of these habits

00:49:04.460 --> 00:49:07.060
and stop continuing them.

00:49:07.060 --> 00:49:10.660
Have you had any
feedback from people on--

00:49:10.660 --> 00:49:13.360
what kind of a feedback have
you had on the book so far?

00:49:13.360 --> 00:49:17.860
ADRIAN MARTIN: Well,
thousands of pictures

00:49:17.860 --> 00:49:20.710
from actual students,
which I didn't

00:49:20.710 --> 00:49:21.950
expect it to be students.

00:49:21.950 --> 00:49:26.350
I expected it to be just
mommies, at the end of the day.

00:49:26.350 --> 00:49:29.000
But no, students
have picked up on it

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:32.840
and yeah, it's been amazing.

00:49:32.840 --> 00:49:35.259
I'm receiving pictures
every single day of recipes

00:49:35.259 --> 00:49:36.300
being made from the book.

00:49:36.300 --> 00:49:39.380
Oh, I made your-- it was
really delicious, you know?

00:49:39.380 --> 00:49:42.640
And that makes my day.

00:49:42.640 --> 00:49:46.639
Also, I was a nervous wreck
when the book came out.

00:49:46.639 --> 00:49:48.930
Because it's your it book,
so you're shaking and stuff.

00:49:48.930 --> 00:49:50.971
So when I walked in to
see it on the shelf, like,

00:49:50.971 --> 00:49:52.570
your heart's racing.

00:49:52.570 --> 00:49:54.990
But I remember walking in--
and actually, it's funny--

00:49:54.990 --> 00:49:55.570
into Eason.

00:49:55.570 --> 00:49:58.226
And there was a guy actually
reading it and I was like, oh!

00:49:58.226 --> 00:49:59.192
Like, walked away.

00:49:59.192 --> 00:50:01.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:01.130 --> 00:50:03.420
I should've stood beside
him, like, so what you think?

00:50:03.420 --> 00:50:05.788
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:07.320 --> 00:50:11.660
But yeah, I was a
nervous wreck about it.

00:50:11.660 --> 00:50:13.134
Yeah, so I was like--

00:50:13.134 --> 00:50:15.550
like, it's either you make it
or you break it with a book.

00:50:15.550 --> 00:50:18.260
It's a big risk to do.

00:50:18.260 --> 00:50:20.620
And if your book
doesn't do well,

00:50:20.620 --> 00:50:22.780
you can say goodbye to
your career, really.

00:50:22.780 --> 00:50:24.520
You won't go as
further on as you can.

00:50:24.520 --> 00:50:27.065
So it's such a massive
risky thing to do.

00:50:27.065 --> 00:50:29.500
I'm just lucky that
it's done so well

00:50:29.500 --> 00:50:32.231
and that I've had massive
feedback from everyone.

00:50:32.231 --> 00:50:33.230
SPEAKER 1: That's great.

00:50:33.230 --> 00:50:34.240
Congratulations.

00:50:34.240 --> 00:50:37.660
And I hope that you get a few
photos from the various people

00:50:37.660 --> 00:50:43.480
in this room today from taking
your recipes home with them.

00:50:43.480 --> 00:50:45.920
Thank you so much for coming
in to speak to us today.

00:50:45.920 --> 00:50:46.961
ADRIAN MARTIN: Thank you.

00:50:46.961 --> 00:50:50.820
[APPLAUSE]

